      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Intermittent fasting does not inherently cause muscle loss when done correctly. Research published in the Journal of Translational Medicine found that participants following a 16:8 fasting protocol while resistance training maintained their lean muscle mass over an 8-week period. The key is consuming adequate protein during your eating window — aim for 0.7 to 1 gram per pound of body weight — and continuing strength training. Muscle loss primarily occurs when people drastically reduce total calorie intake or neglect protein and resistance exercise, not from the timing of meals alone.</p></div>
    </details>
